ious history of desire in Anglo-American religion across three centuries. The pursuit of happiness weaves disparate strands of Anglo-American religious history together. In The Delight Makers, Catherine L. Albanese unravels a theology of desire tying Jonathan Edwards to Ralph Waldo Emerson to the religiously unaffiliated today. As others emphasize redemptive suffering, this tradition stresses the “metaphysical” connection between natural beauty and spiritual fulfillment. In the earth’s abundance, these thinkers see an expansive God intent on fulfilling human desire through prosperity, health, and sexual freedom. Through careful readings of Cotton Mather, Andrew Jackson Davis, William James, Esther Hicks, and more, Albanese reveals how a theology of delight evolved alongside political overtures to natural law and individual liberty in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aMetaphysics. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aliberty, individualism, rights, natural law, delight, desire, pleasure, joy, happiness, theology, religion, secularism, esther hicks, william james, andrew jackson davis, cotton mather, sexual freedom, health, prosperity, success, satisfaction, ambition, god, fulfillment, abundance, spirituality, christianity, suffering, redemption, ralph waldo emerson, jonathan edwards, nonfiction, puritanism, united states, history, philosophy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831107973290 cprintz978022682333140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226823348423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226823348/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles